text: Gravitation is the universal, weakest fundamental force of attraction acting between all matter, governing the motion of celestial bodies and the structure of the cosmos. Formulated by Newton and redefined by Einstein as the curvature of spacetime, gravity keeps planets in orbit, holds our atmosphere, and determines the evolution of stars and galaxies. NASA Space Place (.gov) +2 The Foundation of Gravitational Theory Gravity is an invisible, attractive force that exists between any two objects with mass, increasing with greater mass and decreasing with distance. While often associated with the sensation of weight, gravity's range is infinite, affecting everything from falling apples to the alignment of galaxies. Historically, this concept was foundational to physics, with Sir Isaac Newton proposing that every object in the universe attracts every other object with a force, F = Gm,m₂ Bartleby.com +4 r² From Newton to Einstein Newton's classical mechanics described gravity as an instantaneous force acting at a distance. However, Albert Einstein's 1915 general theory of relativity revolutionized this understanding, defining gravity not as a conventional force, but as a consequence of the curvature of spacetime caused by mass. In this framework, objects (and even light) simply follow the shortest path-geodesics-through the curved space around massive bodies. Bartleby.com +4
